===Etymology===
Recorded since 1538, either (for its original color) from Medieval (=modern) French {{term|carnation||person's color or complexion|lang=fr}} (probably from {{etyl|it}} {{term|carnagione||flesh color|lang=it}}, from {{etyl|LL.}} {{term|carnatio||fleshiness|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|caro||flesh|lang=la}}) or a corruption of {{term|coronation|lang=en}} (from {{term|coronare||to crown|lang=la}}, from {{term|corona||crown|lang=la}}; because of the flower's use in chaplets or from the toothed crown-like look of the petals).

